## The Memory Leak: Two Major Problems

### Problem 1: No cleanup function (the primary leak)

The `useEffect` adds two `window` event listeners but **never removes them**. When the component unmounts (user navigates away), those listeners stay attached to the global `window` object. Each remount adds *more* listeners on top of the orphaned ones.

### Problem 2: No dependency array

Without a dependency array, the effect runs **after every single render**. Every state update (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`) triggers a re-render → which re-runs the effect → which adds *yet another* pair of listeners. Combined with the missing cleanup, this is catastrophic: a single scroll event fires N handlers, each calling `setState`, causing N more renders, each attaching more handlers — exponential accumulation.

### Why anonymous arrow functions break cleanup

Even if you *tried* to call `removeEventListener`, you couldn't, because:

```js
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });   // anonymous function A
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // anonymous function B — different reference!
```

`removeEventListener` works by **reference identity**. The function you pass to remove must be the *exact same function object* you passed to add. Two inline arrow functions with identical bodies are still two distinct objects, so the removal silently does nothing. You **must** keep a named reference.

## The Lifecycle: how handlers accumulate

```
Mount → effect runs → 2 listeners attached
  ↓ scroll fires → handler calls setState x3
  ↓ re-render → effect runs AGAIN (no deps) → 2 MORE listeners
  ↓ next scroll → now 4 handlers fire → 12 setState calls → 4 more renders...
  ↓ ...runaway growth within a single mount
Unmount (navigate away) → NO cleanup → all listeners orphaned, retained via closure
Remount (navigate back) → starts over, piled on top of the orphans
```

The closures also retain `lastScrollY` from stale renders, so each leaked handler holds onto old state — memory is never reclaimed and direction calculations become wrong.

## React 18 Strict Mode makes it visible in development

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects**: it runs the effect, immediately runs its cleanup, then runs the effect again. This is a deliberate stress-test to surface exactly this class of bug. With a correct cleanup, you'd see add → remove → add (net: one set of listeners). With this buggy code, the missing cleanup means the double-invocation just doubles the leak immediately on mount — so you notice duplicate logs/handlers right away instead of only in production. It's a feature designed to catch missing cleanup.

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // Track last scroll position in a ref so it doesn't trigger re-renders
    // and isn't a stale closure value inside the handler.
    const lastScrollY = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named handler references so we can remove the SAME function objects.
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollY.current = currentScrollY;
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup: runs on unmount AND before the effect re-runs.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // Empty deps: attach listeners ONCE on mount, clean up ONCE on unmount.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

### What changed and why functionality is preserved

| Fix | Reason |
|-----|--------|
| **Named handlers** (`handleScroll`, `handleResize`) | Stable references so `removeEventListener` can match and remove them |
| **`return () => {...}` cleanup** | Detaches listeners on unmount — nothing orphaned across navigations |
| **`[]` dependency array** | Effect runs once on mount; state updates no longer re-attach listeners |
| **`lastScrollY` → `useRef`** | This was *display-irrelevant* internal state. As `useState` it caused extra renders and, with `[]` deps, would have become a stale closure. A ref gives the handler the always-current value without re-rendering |

**Functional equivalence:** still tracks `scrollY`, computes up/down direction by comparing against the previous position, logs on resize, and renders the same fixed overlay. The only behavioral change is correctness improvements — direction is now computed against the genuinely-latest value instead of a possibly-stale state snapshot.

> **Note on the original `lastScrollY` as state:** I moved it to a ref because it was never rendered and only read inside the handler. If you genuinely needed it in the UI, the alternative is keeping it as state and using the functional updater pattern (`setScrollDirection`/comparison inside a `setLastScrollY(prev => ...)`) so you can still keep `[]` deps without a stale closure. For this component, the ref is the cleaner fit.

